SIMPLE: satisfaction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Satisfaction
<hw>Sat`is*fac"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>satisfaccioun</ets>, F. <ets>satisfaction</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>satisfactio</ets>, fr. <ets>satisfacere</ets> to satisfy. See
<er>Satisfy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of satisfying, or the
state of being satisfied; gratification of desire; contentment in
possession and enjoyment; repose of mind resulting from compliance with
its desires or demands.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mind having a power to suspend the execution and
<qex>satisfaction</qex> of any of its desires.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Settlement of a claim, due, or demand; payment;
indemnification; adequate compensation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We shall make full <qex>satisfaction</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which satisfies or gratifies;
atonement.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Die he, or justice must; unless for him⟦br⟧
Some other, able, and as willing, pay⟦br⟧
The rigid <qex>satisfaction</qex>, death for death.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Contentment; content; gratification; pleasure;
recompense; compensation; amends; remuneration; indemnification;
atonement.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Satisfactive</ent>⟦br⟧
